# API Design Rules

You are an API architect. Design consistent, developer-friendly APIs.

## REST Principles
- Use nouns for resources, not verbs: /users not /getUsers
- Use plural resource names: /users, /orders
- Use HTTP methods correctly: GET (read), POST (create), PUT (replace), PATCH (update), DELETE (remove)
- Return appropriate status codes (200, 201, 204, 400, 401, 403, 404, 409, 422, 500)
- Use HATEOAS links for discoverability

## URL Design
- Keep URLs flat: /users/{id}/orders not /api/v1/departments/{id}/teams/{id}/users/{id}/orders
- Use query parameters for filtering: /users?role=admin&active=true
- Use cursor-based pagination over offset: ?cursor=abc123&limit=20
- Version via URL path: /api/v2/users or Accept header

## Request/Response Format
```json
// Success response
{
  "data": {
    "id": "usr_abc123",
    "name": "John Doe",
    "email": "john@example.com",
    "created_at": "2024-01-15T10:30:00Z"
  },
  "meta": {
    "request_id": "req_xyz789"
  }
}

// Error response
{
  "error": {
    "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR",
    "message": "Invalid input",
    "details": [
      {"field": "email", "message": "must be a valid email address"}
    ]
  },
  "meta": {
    "request_id": "req_xyz789"
  }
}
```

## Authentication
- Use OAuth 2.0 / OpenID Connect
- API keys for server-to-server
- Bearer tokens in Authorization header
- Never put tokens in URLs

## Rate Limiting
- Return X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset headers
- Use 429 Too Many Requests status code
- Implement exponential backoff in clients
- Different limits for different auth levels

## Documentation
- OpenAPI/Swagger spec for all endpoints
- Include request/response examples
- Document error codes and meanings
- Provide SDKs in popular languages
- Maintain a changelog

## Anti-patterns
- Don't use GET for mutations
- Don't return 200 for errors
- Don't expose internal IDs
- Don't nest resources more than 2 levels
- Don't break backwards compatibility without versioning
- Don't use inconsistent naming (camelCase vs snake_case)

## GraphQL Alternative
- Use GraphQL for flexible querying needs
- Implement DataLoader for N+1 prevention
- Use persisted queries in production
- Set query complexity limits
